# GraalJS Script Integration Plan
# Adds generic JavaScript scripting capability via GraalVM's GraalJS engine.
# Two initial integration points: computed attribute values + playbook script steps.
# Designed as a shared service so future callers (approval rules, etc.) can reuse it.

## Overview

Add an embedded JavaScript engine (GraalJS) that runs sandboxed scripts in-process.
Scripts receive a context object with domain-specific data and return a result.
The engine is exposed as a generic `ScriptEvaluationService` consumed by multiple features.

---

## Phase 1: Core Engine — ScriptEvaluationService

### 1.1 Add GraalJS dependency

File: pom.xml

Add to <dependencies>:
  - org.graalvm.polyglot:polyglot (latest 24.x)
  - org.graalvm.polyglot:js (latest 24.x, runtime scope)

These are standalone JARs — no full GraalVM JDK required.

### 1.2 Create ScriptEvaluationService

File: src/main/java/com/ldapadmin/script/ScriptEvaluationService.java

@Service class with:

  - Shared GraalVM `Engine` instance (thread-safe, expensive to create, reuse it).
    Created in @PostConstruct, closed in @PreDestroy.

  - Primary method:
      Object evaluate(String script, Map<String, Object> bindings, Duration timeout)
    Steps:
      1. Create a sandboxed Context per invocation:
         Context.newBuilder("js")
           .engine(sharedEngine)
           .allowIO(IOAccess.NONE)
           .allowNativeAccess(false)
           .allowCreateThread(false)
           .allowHostAccess(HostAccess.NONE)       // no calling back into Java
           .allowEnvironmentAccess(EnvironmentAccess.NONE)
           .option("js.ecmascript-version", "2022")
           .build()
      2. Bind each entry from `bindings` map into the JS global scope as read-only.
         For Map values, convert to JS-friendly proxy via Value.asValue().
      3. Execute the script string within the context.
      4. Extract and return the result (auto-convert Value to String/Boolean/Map/List).
      5. Close the Context in a finally block.

  - Timeout enforcement:
      Use Context.close(true) from a scheduled thread if execution exceeds `timeout`.
      Default timeout from config: app.script.timeout-ms (default 5000).

  - Convenience overloads:
      String evaluateToString(script, bindings)  — calls evaluate(), toString() on result.
      Map<String,Object> evaluateToMap(script, bindings) — for structured results.

  - Error handling:
      Catch PolyglotException. Wrap in a ScriptExecutionException (new custom exception)
      that includes: script source (truncated), error message, line number.
      The GlobalExceptionHandler maps ScriptExecutionException → 422 Unprocessable Entity.

### 1.3 Configuration properties

File: src/main/java/com/ldapadmin/config/AppProperties.java

Add nested class:
  @Getter @Setter
  public static class Script {
      private int timeoutMs = 5000;       // max execution time per script
      private int maxOutputLength = 10000; // truncate results beyond this
  }

Add field to AppProperties:
  @Valid private Script script = new Script();

No mandatory config — sensible defaults work out of the box.

### 1.4 Custom exception

File: src/main/java/com/ldapadmin/exception/ScriptExecutionException.java

public class ScriptExecutionException extends RuntimeException
  - Fields: scriptSnippet (String, first 200 chars), lineNumber (int)
  - Extends RuntimeException

Add handler in GlobalExceptionHandler:
  @ExceptionHandler(ScriptExecutionException.class) → 422

### 1.5 Unit tests

File: src/test/java/com/ldapadmin/script/ScriptEvaluationServiceTest.java

Test cases:
  - Simple string return: "ctx.firstName + '.' + ctx.lastName" → "john.doe"
  - Conditional logic: ternary returning different values
  - Timeout enforcement: infinite loop → ScriptExecutionException
  - Sandbox: attempting Java.type() or file access → exception
  - Null/missing bindings handled gracefully
  - Map result extraction works

